nal Psychology             Special Education           Department of Curriculum and Instruction   We are a community of more than 30 faculty and 500 undergraduate and graduate students who are engaged in critical scholarship, practice, and praxis, and who address the most pressing issues in education, both locally and globally. The department develops scholars, researchers and leaders in the areas of curriculum and instruction; literacy (language and culture); math and science education; bilingual/ESL education; and teacher education.    About the Department         Department of Educational Policy Studies    The Educational Policy Studies Department offers opportunities to study social foundations of education, educational organizations and leadership, and education policy analysis.  The department’s work emphasizes the analysis of urban contexts, and understanding and addressing educational problems in those contexts. Its programs prepare students for successful careers in urban educational research and policy analysis, and in transformational leadership of urban schools.     About the Department         Department of Educational Psychology   The Department of Educational Psychology is internationally known for its rigorous degree programs, esteemed faculty, and commitment to urban education and test fairness. Our work focuses on understanding how children’s ethnicity, culture, class, and gender impact their development and learning, and we are dedicated to developing and applying fair approaches of measurement, evaluation, statistics and assessment to support such efforts.    Department of Educational Psychology         Department of Special Education   The Department of Special Education (SPED) is a community of dedicated scholars, researchers, teachers and practitioners working toward innovation and access to improve the education of children and adolescents with disabilities – particularly in urban school environments. The community also is a forceful advocate for special education through outreach service programs and groundbreaking research.    About the Department            Academics    Back to main content           Degree Programs     BA Human Development and Learning     Degree Requirements    How to Apply    Focus Areas, Credentials & Minors    Program Faculty    Frequently Asked Questions    Guaranteed Professional Program Admissions (GPPA)      BA Urban Education – Elementary Education     Degree Requirements    How to Apply    Endorsements    Where can I teach?    Guaranteed Professional Program Admissions (GPPA)    FAQs: Candidacy    Call Me MISTER     Application Process    Supporting a MISTER    Meet the MISTERs        MEd Early Childhood Education     Degree Requirements    How to Apply    Licensure, Endorsements & Credentials    Alternative Licensure      MEd Educational Policy Studies     Degree Requirements    How to Apply      MEd Educational Studies     Degree Requirements    How to Apply    Endorsements    Alumni Testimonials    Frequently Asked Questions      MEd Language, Literacies and Learning     Degree Requirements    How to Apply    Endorsements    Frequently Asked Questions    Literacies@Chicago      MEd Measurement, Evaluation, Statistics & Assessment     Degree Requirements    How to Apply    Program Faculty    Student Testimonials    Frequently Asked Questions      MEd Measurement, Evaluation, Statistics & Assessment Online     Degree Requirements    Application Process    Frequently Asked Questions      MEd Science Education     Degree Requirements    How to Apply    Endorsements    Fellowships & Aid    Project SEEEC    Program in the News      MEd Special Education     Degree Requirements    How to Apply    Licensure & Endorsements    FAQs    Scholarships & Financial Support    Alumni Profiles      MEd Youth Development     Degree Requirements    How to Apply    Program Faculty    Alumni Profiles    Frequently Asked Questions    Prospective Field Site Form      MEd Urban Higher Education